// Then at some point in your component, you can call this function, like in an event handler
```

In this example, `sendPostRequest` is a function that uses the value of `documentTitle` as part of the Axios POST request. This is perfectly fine because, in functional components, the state values are accessible from any function within the component.

If you are calling `sendPostRequest` from an event handler or a `useEffect` hook within the same component, `documentTitle` will have the most recent value that you have set using `setDocumentTitle`.

If `sendPostRequest` is being defined outside of the component where `documentTitle` state is managed, then you will need to pass `documentTitle` as a parameter to the function:

```jsx
const sendPostRequest = async (title) => {
    // similar as above, use title in the request payload
};
```

And then call it like this within your component:

```jsx
sendPostRequest(documentTitle);
```

Remember, in JavaScript, strings are immutable, so whenever you set the `documentTitle` state, React makes sure you get the current value whenever you access the state variable in your functional component.

